WEBVTT

1
00:00:05.510 --> 00:00:07.640
We finally made it!

2
00:00:10.940 --> 00:00:13.880
The Americas!

3
00:00:22.350 --> 00:00:25.170
It was such a long trip!

4
00:00:25.170 --> 00:00:27.170
At long last...

5
00:00:27.170 --> 00:00:31.710
Land!

6
00:00:28.710 --> 00:00:31.710
Meat!

7
00:00:35.800 --> 00:00:40.390
We didn't get to eat much 
meat while we were at sea.

8
00:00:44.970 --> 00:00:51.400
The battle team may be in need of 
animal protein after all that training.

9
00:00:53.840 --> 00:00:55.040
That's right!

10
00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:58.480
We might be able to hunt wild 
animals once we're ashore!

11
00:00:58.480 --> 00:01:00.780
What kind of animals are 
there in the Americas?

12
00:01:00.780 --> 00:01:03.640
I've never traveled abroad before!

13
00:01:04.710 --> 00:01:07.910
This wasn't exactly the 
vacation I had in mind!

14
00:01:07.910 --> 00:01:09.410
Vacation...

15
00:01:11.320 --> 00:01:15.260
Meathead here may have 
the right idea. though.

16
00:01:19.390 --> 00:01:21.970
Look. Past the fog.

17
00:01:58.960 --> 00:02:00.250
Of course.

18
00:02:00.250 --> 00:02:02.550
We knew it would be like this.

19
00:02:02.550 --> 00:02:06.850
Then again. this is our first 
time overseas in this new world.

20
00:02:06.850 --> 00:02:10.480
We didn't know how the world was going to be.

21
00:02:11.740 --> 00:02:15.770
Who knows? The Fake Lilian 
story might have been true.

22
00:02:15.770 --> 00:02:18.100
Maybe it was just Japan 
that was still petrified.

23
00:02:18.860 --> 00:02:22.020
Maybe the world had already 
gotten back to normal.

24
00:02:22.020 --> 00:02:26.520
Or maybe they'd fought off the 
petrification beam right from the start.

25
00:02:27.710 --> 00:02:30.510
Somewhere deep down. we thought. maybe...

26
00:02:30.920 --> 00:02:34.580
Just maybe! You know?

27
00:02:46.340 --> 00:02:48.060
Look at that cape.

28
00:02:48.470 --> 00:02:51.380
There's a giant clump of statues there.

29
00:02:52.450 --> 00:02:53.520
You're right.

30
00:02:54.230 --> 00:02:55.520
Why?

31
00:02:56.770 --> 00:02:58.990
Probably a huge car crash.

32
00:03:00.450 --> 00:03:05.660
All the cars must have withered away. 
leaving only the statues behind.

33
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:08.630
We're on water.

34
00:03:08.630 --> 00:03:10.080
Why would there be cars here?

35
00:03:12.050 --> 00:03:14.040
In fact. this place was filled with cars.

36
00:03:15.760 --> 00:03:18.280
I passed by here on my own boat.

37
00:03:18.990 --> 00:03:20.570
Several thousand years ago.

38
00:03:21.630 --> 00:03:26.040
this was the gate to the Pacific.

39
00:03:26.600 --> 00:03:32.280
The beautiful. red Golden Gate Bridge. 
shining amid the San Francisco fog.

40
00:03:34.830 --> 00:03:38.080
It really is all gone.

41
00:03:38.530 --> 00:03:40.530
Everything humanity built is gone.

42
00:03:41.200 --> 00:03:46.500
Part of me was still hoping 
they'd help us out.

43
00:03:46.500 --> 00:03:48.170
Y-Yeah...

44
00:03:48.170 --> 00:03:49.190
Nope.

45
00:03:49.570 --> 00:03:51.080
That's not it. guys.

46
00:03:51.910 --> 00:03:54.310
Once we get and raise corn.

47
00:03:54.310 --> 00:03:59.840
the power of science will help us revive 
all the statues around the world!

48
00:04:00.500 --> 00:04:01.670
Yeah.

49
00:04:02.670 --> 00:04:05.200
We're the ones going to help them.

50
00:04:06.450 --> 00:04:10.300
All 7.8 billion people.

51
00:05:41.980 --> 00:05:46.990
Light Trap in the Darkness

52
00:05:53.190 --> 00:05:54.250
Finally!

53
00:05:54.250 --> 00:05:55.670
We're in the US!

54
00:05:56.120 --> 00:05:59.170
Landfall!

55
00:06:01.300 --> 00:06:04.880
Lilian's homeland.

56
00:06:06.260 --> 00:06:08.310
So this is America!

57
00:06:08.310 --> 00:06:12.270
I've heard a lot about it. so I've been 
wondering what it's really like... but...

58
00:06:14.170 --> 00:06:17.020
It doesn't look much different from Japan.

59
00:06:18.310 --> 00:06:20.270
It's just a forest.

60
00:06:24.570 --> 00:06:27.830
I guess all the distinctly 
American landmarks are all gone.

61
00:06:27.830 --> 00:06:29.410
Of course it isn't recognizable.

62
00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:34.410
It's a pine cone!

63
00:06:35.980 --> 00:06:38.680
I-It's way huge!

64
00:06:39.580 --> 00:06:41.630
That's a sequoia.

65
00:06:41.630 --> 00:06:43.670
Sequoia?

66
00:06:44.930 --> 00:06:46.260
This guy.

67
00:06:47.230 --> 00:06:50.100
Holy crap. it's enormous!

68
00:06:51.250 --> 00:06:57.770
I've seen plenty of forests. 
but I've never seen such a huge tree!

69
00:06:58.050 --> 00:07:02.050
Sequoias get over 80 meters tall.

70
00:07:02.050 --> 00:07:04.920
They're ridiculously huge. 
The biggest on Earth. in fact.

71
00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:07.780
E-Eighty meters?!

72
00:07:14.780 --> 00:07:19.370
Even after civilization's fall. 
the world operates on its own scale.

73
00:07:21.360 --> 00:07:23.960
Damn. America...

74
00:07:28.800 --> 00:07:31.430
We'll split into two teams 
here at the Sacramento River.

75
00:07:31.930 --> 00:07:34.750
The resource acquisition team 
will remain on the ship.

76
00:07:34.750 --> 00:07:37.970
and the corn scout team 
will head toward the interior.

77
00:07:38.510 --> 00:07:42.060
I assume the battle team will 
be escorting the scout team

78
00:07:42.060 --> 00:07:43.920
to deal with any wild animal encounters.

79
00:08:00.580 --> 00:08:04.750
Let's get this corn search started! 
No stone unturned!

80
00:08:04.750 --> 00:08:07.570
Yeah. that's not happening.

81
00:08:07.570 --> 00:08:09.760
You have no idea how big the US is.

82
00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:16.860
We aren't even sure America's beloved 
corn hasn't already hybridized.

83
00:08:17.640 --> 00:08:19.380
There's a region called the Corn Belt.

84
00:08:19.380 --> 00:08:22.140
If there's still corn around. 
that's where we'll likely find it.

85
00:08:23.220 --> 00:08:26.580
On the west coast. our best 
bet is northern California.

86
00:08:30.390 --> 00:08:35.260
We'll go through San Francisco Bay to 
the Sacramento River and the City area.

87
00:08:35.260 --> 00:08:37.420
Wait. wait. Senku-chan.

88
00:08:37.420 --> 00:08:42.040
Most people don't know American geography.

89
00:08:42.630 --> 00:08:46.710
Okay. well. point is. we should 
find corn up this river. right?

90
00:08:46.930 --> 00:08:48.320
Let's get moving!

91
00:08:48.680 --> 00:08:52.810
Chrome-chan's so quick to find 
optimism in new situations.

92
00:08:52.810 --> 00:08:54.960
That's why you're our exploration leader.

93
00:09:00.260 --> 00:09:02.170
Fall is almost over.

94
00:09:02.170 --> 00:09:05.040
We're at the end of corn season.

95
00:09:05.040 --> 00:09:06.770
Let's hope we made it in time.

96
00:09:07.170 --> 00:09:09.270
Yeah. that won't be an issue.

97
00:09:10.260 --> 00:09:13.080
The planet goes through a 
thing called precession.

98
00:09:13.080 --> 00:09:16.290
It's the same thing as how 
a top teeters as it spins.

99
00:09:15.840 --> 00:09:21.160
Precession

100
00:09:16.690 --> 00:09:22.990
Luckily for us. thanks to the planet's axis 
moving slightly over the past 3.700 years.

101
00:09:22.990 --> 00:09:26.250
the climate is offset by about nine days.

102
00:09:27.960 --> 00:09:29.880
So we just barely made it!

103
00:09:30.480 --> 00:09:31.950
What has me more worried

104
00:09:31.950 --> 00:09:35.790
is the subtle ecological changes as 
a result of the change in climate.

105
00:09:35.790 --> 00:09:39.510
We'd better hope we don't get 
attacked by any big creatures.

106
00:09:40.010 --> 00:09:43.750
I'd enjoy it if we did get 
attacked by a big creature.

107
00:09:44.570 --> 00:09:45.600
Yeah.

108
00:09:47.990 --> 00:09:50.150
Wait. what? Isn't it the opposite?

109
00:09:58.990 --> 00:10:01.700
There you go jinxing it again. Senku-chan!

110
00:10:01.700 --> 00:10:04.800
I get it now. though... Seriously...

111
00:10:05.330 --> 00:10:07.340
It's not bad luck or anything!

112
00:10:07.340 --> 00:10:09.260
There's no such thing as luck!

113
00:10:09.260 --> 00:10:10.630
Science man Senku is just

114
00:10:10.630 --> 00:10:15.090
telling us the worst-case scenario 
because he knows it'll happen!

115
00:10:18.930 --> 00:10:20.900
It's a float of American crocodiles!

116
00:10:23.100 --> 00:10:25.890
There's so freaking many of them!

117
00:10:38.130 --> 00:10:39.110
Meat!

118
00:10:39.110 --> 00:10:40.250
Meat!

119
00:10:40.250 --> 00:10:41.410
Meat!

120
00:10:43.320 --> 00:10:45.030
Meat!

121
00:10:45.030 --> 00:10:46.500
Meat!

122
00:10:46.500 --> 00:10:48.490
So that's what this is about!

123
00:10:48.490 --> 00:10:50.910
That's why you were hoping we'd get attacked!

124
00:10:50.910 --> 00:10:52.860
Meat!

125
00:10:54.490 --> 00:10:57.910
I'm grateful to the circle of life.

126
00:11:00.480 --> 00:11:02.390
Well. this is something.

127
00:11:03.640 --> 00:11:08.350
The almighty all-stars!

128
00:11:32.380 --> 00:11:34.500
We're in the US. which means...

129
00:11:35.450 --> 00:11:38.510
We aren't leaving before we have some of this.

130
00:12:00.750 --> 00:12:02.580
Please enjoy.

131
00:12:02.580 --> 00:12:04.780
Crocodile burgers.

132
00:12:06.660 --> 00:12:09.040
Hamburgers!

133
00:12:09.260 --> 00:12:11.400
Hamburgers?

134
00:12:11.860 --> 00:12:14.670
You eat them like this.

135
00:12:25.740 --> 00:12:28.850
It's so tasty!

136
00:12:31.850 --> 00:12:34.520
Damn. it's so good!

137
00:12:34.520 --> 00:12:37.020
How is it so juicy?!

138
00:12:37.020 --> 00:12:39.230
I've never had anything like it!

139
00:12:59.540 --> 00:13:00.340
Senku.

140
00:13:02.120 --> 00:13:04.060
One of the crocodiles had swallowed this.

141
00:13:06.650 --> 00:13:08.290
Is there something inside it?

142
00:13:18.930 --> 00:13:20.060
Corn!

143
00:13:23.410 --> 00:13:26.330
This is the fabled American corn?

144
00:13:27.770 --> 00:13:29.660
Landed right in our hands.

145
00:13:30.150 --> 00:13:34.230
We've found the key to reviving 
all of humanity upstream!

146
00:13:38.510 --> 00:13:40.920
This is the life-giving corn!

147
00:13:40.920 --> 00:13:42.150
Yup.

148
00:13:42.150 --> 00:13:45.290
The OP corn crop of the Americas.

149
00:13:45.290 --> 00:13:47.640
The great Yellow Dent.

150
00:13:47.640 --> 00:13:49.620
OP crop...

151
00:13:50.570 --> 00:13:52.400
It tastes like ass. though.

152
00:13:52.400 --> 00:13:56.310
But we can get alcohol out 
of it insanely efficiently.

153
00:13:57.670 --> 00:14:01.960
Which means we're finally 
reviving the whole world!

154
00:14:01.960 --> 00:14:03.190
Hang on!

155
00:14:03.190 --> 00:14:06.950
We're almost there. statues of America!

156
00:14:07.280 --> 00:14:11.130
Although I have no idea how 
much of this corn is left.

157
00:14:11.130 --> 00:14:12.010
All good.

158
00:14:12.010 --> 00:14:15.460
We only need a little. 
and we can grow a ton more.

159
00:14:15.460 --> 00:14:17.990
It'll be a race against time either way.

160
00:14:18.710 --> 00:14:23.240
We need to face our enemy 
before they get to us first.

161
00:14:23.240 --> 00:14:25.090
To face Why-Man!

162
00:14:25.090 --> 00:14:26.180
Yup.

163
00:14:26.180 --> 00:14:29.550
We're gonna get right to 
work making Corn City!

164
00:14:35.270 --> 00:14:37.180
Corn grains!

165
00:14:38.410 --> 00:14:40.690
They're flowing down the 
river one after another.

166
00:14:42.070 --> 00:14:44.020
H-Hyoga-sama...

167
00:14:45.960 --> 00:14:48.990
We can be sure they're growing up ahead.

168
00:14:48.990 --> 00:14:51.570
There's got to be a crap ton!

169
00:14:54.950 --> 00:15:00.230
Does corn really drift conveniently 
down the river. though?

170
00:15:03.300 --> 00:15:06.190
Hello. <i>Perseus</i> here.

171
00:15:06.190 --> 00:15:09.110
<i>Heya. Scout team here.</i>

172
00:15:09.110 --> 00:15:11.700
<i>We found corn on the river.</i>

173
00:15:13.810 --> 00:15:16.900
We haven't actually found it growing.

174
00:15:16.900 --> 00:15:18.580
We need information.

175
00:15:18.580 --> 00:15:23.100
So let us know if you find 
any floating downstream.

176
00:15:23.100 --> 00:15:24.610
<i>Okay. roger.</i>

177
00:15:24.830 --> 00:15:26.560
You heard them. boys!

178
00:15:26.560 --> 00:15:30.190
Keep your eyes peeled! 
Don't miss a single thing!

179
00:15:32.340 --> 00:15:33.530
All right!

180
00:15:33.530 --> 00:15:35.220
Let's do this!

181
00:16:33.610 --> 00:16:34.800
It's around here.

182
00:16:35.020 --> 00:16:38.880
You mentioned a bunch of 
confusing place names earlier.

183
00:16:38.880 --> 00:16:41.790
The Sacramento City area. was it?

184
00:16:49.240 --> 00:16:51.900
What are you making in 
such a hurry. Senku-chan?

185
00:16:53.490 --> 00:16:56.250
A white cloth over the light?

186
00:17:00.090 --> 00:17:03.130
You'll attract bugs with 
such a bright light at night.

187
00:17:03.130 --> 00:17:05.400
That's the whole point.

188
00:17:05.400 --> 00:17:07.000
It's a light trap.

189
00:17:08.340 --> 00:17:13.480
We can tell what's in the area from whether 
or not we attract phototactic bugs.

190
00:17:14.230 --> 00:17:16.560
If I'm right about this...

191
00:17:33.780 --> 00:17:36.450
European corn borers.

192
00:17:36.450 --> 00:17:38.740
These moths thrive on corn.

193
00:17:39.320 --> 00:17:42.380
There's a boatload of corn nearby.

194
00:17:43.680 --> 00:17:46.430
Butterflies. huh? They're beautiful.

195
00:17:46.430 --> 00:17:47.920
Nah. they're moths.

196
00:17:48.220 --> 00:17:51.920
Butterflies are moths. 
We humans just gave them a different name.

197
00:17:52.980 --> 00:17:55.050
They have a mystical beauty about them. huh?

198
00:17:57.440 --> 00:17:58.690
Kohaku...

199
00:17:58.690 --> 00:18:00.710
Actually. everyone from the village...

200
00:18:01.150 --> 00:18:05.090
Have you guys ever even 
seen this kind of moth?

201
00:18:07.290 --> 00:18:10.090
Now that you mention it. 
I've never seen it before.

202
00:18:10.500 --> 00:18:12.770
I've never even thought about 
different kinds of moths.

203
00:18:13.010 --> 00:18:16.200
These guys eat cloth more 
than they do grains.

204
00:18:16.200 --> 00:18:19.780
In other words. their numbers 
should have dwindled

205
00:18:19.780 --> 00:18:22.530
quite a bit since the humans vanished.

206
00:18:23.230 --> 00:18:28.370
How did we end up with so 
many in so little time?

207
00:18:28.370 --> 00:18:31.710
It almost makes me wonder if 
there's a giant corn farm nearby.

208
00:18:33.240 --> 00:18:35.760
What's up. Senku? You look so serious.

209
00:18:35.760 --> 00:18:37.760
We're reviving all of humanity.

210
00:18:37.760 --> 00:18:41.090
What more could you hope 
for than plenty of corn?

211
00:18:50.080 --> 00:18:51.210
I sense...

212
00:19:06.580 --> 00:19:07.640
Bloodlust!

213
00:19:08.720 --> 00:19:09.710
What is it?

214
00:19:09.710 --> 00:19:11.160
A beast of some sort?

215
00:19:11.160 --> 00:19:14.460
Nothing to worry about with our elite group!

216
00:19:14.460 --> 00:19:16.470
It's not convincing when 
you say it while hiding.

217
00:19:16.470 --> 00:19:19.260
Do you recognize its ki?

218
00:19:19.530 --> 00:19:22.260
No. there's no such thing as ki.

219
00:19:22.570 --> 00:19:27.340
Though I do think we're perceiving 
adrenaline byproducts and such.

220
00:19:27.990 --> 00:19:30.520
Not that I can really say.

221
00:19:32.070 --> 00:19:33.260
<i>Think...</i>

222
00:19:37.310 --> 00:19:39.560
<i>I vowed to protect them.</i>

223
00:19:42.860 --> 00:19:45.870
<i>This faint scent on the air...</i>

224
00:19:49.880 --> 00:19:51.190
<i>Gun smoke?!</i>

225
00:19:51.780 --> 00:19:53.490
<i>From a used firearm?!</i>

226
00:19:53.960 --> 00:19:57.810
The enemy is indeed proper.

227
00:20:00.830 --> 00:20:07.060
It seems we were the ones who 
were attracted to the light trap.

228
00:20:14.060 --> 00:20:15.650
All hands. to the boat!

229
00:20:37.530 --> 00:20:38.380
Machine gun!

230
00:20:39.350 --> 00:20:40.800
What the heck is that?!

231
00:20:44.910 --> 00:20:48.240
Don't underestimate a sailor's maneuvering!

232
00:20:51.630 --> 00:20:53.320
Water barrier!

233
00:21:14.330 --> 00:21:16.400
Why did they find out?

234
00:21:20.140 --> 00:21:24.080
We're saved thanks to 
Tsukasa's superhuman senses.

235
00:21:24.400 --> 00:21:26.430
Are you all relatively safe?

236
00:21:26.430 --> 00:21:27.880
How?

237
00:21:27.880 --> 00:21:30.090
Who would have a machine gun?

238
00:21:30.510 --> 00:21:33.010
I thought there were no more humans left.

239
00:21:33.010 --> 00:21:35.980
So the US was spared?

240
00:21:35.980 --> 00:21:37.390
That can't be it.

241
00:21:37.390 --> 00:21:40.110
It wouldn't explain why those 
statues were left there.

242
00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:42.720
The only possibility...

243
00:21:43.220 --> 00:21:46.320
is that someone revived 
on their own. like Senku.

244
00:21:49.970 --> 00:21:51.970
And they're growing corn.

245
00:21:53.130 --> 00:21:57.380
That would be hella fortunate.

246
00:21:59.210 --> 00:22:01.990
In the worst case. we're going 
to have a proper science duel

247
00:22:01.990 --> 00:22:03.610
with a science user on the Dark Side.

248
00:22:05.330 --> 00:22:09.070
We're gonna have to win that fight.

249
00:22:10.820 --> 00:22:13.580
This is stupid exhilarating!

250
00:23:52.030 --> 00:23:54.990
Next Episode

251
00:23:54.990 --> 00:23:59.990
This is a work of fiction. but the plants. 
animals. and production methods described are based on reality.
Foraging and making things on your own accord is extremely dangerous
and. in some cases. illegal. Please do not imitate without expertise.
